The losers remain challengers
HARARE: Before this month's presidential elections, I was convinced that irregularities in the elections would have serious consequences for Zimbabwe itself and the entire southern Africa.
Despite the shadows of war and terrorism, I called for fair and free elections.
The people of Zimbabwe did not get them.
Instead, they received terrorism.
In the two years leading up to the presidential elections, the people of Zimbabwe were victims of intimidation, harassment, and threats by the party of Robert Mugabe, the African National Union - Patriotic Front (ZANU-PF), whose program is state-subsidized terrorism.
The ZANU-terrorism is attributed to the thugs among the veterans from Zimbabwe's independence war two decades ago, the government militias, and young men, all of whom are supported by the police.
The result of intimidation and violence was that my party, the Movement for Democratic Change (MDC), did not reach the electorate in large parts, particularly in rural areas.
Moreover, my opponent President Mugabe's government effectively disenfranchised hundreds of thousands of voters in the cities, especially in the capital Harare and in Chitungwiza.
Due to there not being enough polling stations, in my opinion more than 360,000 people stood in line alone in Harare and Chitungwiza, without being able to cast their ballot.
I doubt the legitimacy of the election result further because Mugabe's militias prevented the MDC from posting observers at over 52% of rural polling stations.
By the end of the voting, our party lacked observers at 6 out of 10 rural polling stations.
This means that Mugabe's supporters were able to impose their will at these polling stations.
We are currently compiling a comprehensive list of all polling stations that were controlled solely by ZANU supporters.
In our preliminary investigations, a pattern has even emerged at this early stage: in these polling stations, most votes went to Mugabe.
Given the overwhelming evidence, I cannot accept the result of the presidential elections, in which the incumbent president Robert Mugabe emerged as the winner with 56% of the 3 million cast votes.
The official result does not reflect the true will of Zimbabwe's people and is considered illegitimate by them.
The people of Zimbabwe were denied the right to freely and democratically elect a president of their choice.
The struggle over the election results is a political issue that must be resolved politically.
Food and fuel are scarce, jobs are being lost, and inflation exceeds 100%.
The people of Zimbabwe were brave and determined, and they deserve to have this acknowledged.
Maybe it's not too late for that.
I am writing this text in sorrow, because Mugabe's regime still disregards the will of the people.
No matter what happens, I will stand as a loyal servant by the side of the people and walk the road with them to the end.
The government might arrest me.
I was also arrested for high treason before the elections.
In the worst case, they even want to kill me.
But the government will never be able to break the will of the people to assert their rights and power.
It lies in our hands to bring about a democratic transformation.
In the coming days, we will experience moments of fear, but we must not allow despair to overcome us.
The political transformation is irreversible.
But we must be ready to pay a high price for our freedom.
President Mugabe and his henchmen fear the people, and we have heard that they will do everything to kill the messenger of the message.
Should it come to that, I ask the people of Zimbabwe only to stay strong and see through what we have begun together.
There are many heroes among the people of Zimbabwe - heroes who waited for hours to vote, heroes who would not be intimidated.
It is the voices of heroes of a new Zimbabwe that must be heard in the world.
We have traveled a very steep path together to bring about a democratic transformation in our country.
In the history of humanity, a people has rarely had to endure such violence and still managed to preserve kindness and exuberance.
I notice that the people of Zimbabwe are impatient.
I understand.
But for a political process to occur, they must be patient and wait.
You cannot simply ignore these elections, but you must also not fall for Mugabe's provocations and resort to violence.
The people of Zimbabwe want change, in the constitution, in the legal system, legitimate change, and they will achieve it, despite all obstacles.
We know that we are not alone.
We know that electoral fraud occurs throughout Africa.
In most African countries, irregularities, fraud, and deception seem to be standard during elections.
In Africa, there is always some kind of crisis due to elections.
It is sad, but the entire continent is plagued by governments that resort to unfair means when it comes time to grant people their right to vote.
But those who want something else can hope.
Zimbabwe's struggle is not yet over.
There is still time to draw lessons from our experience for Africa and the world.
My people are in the hour of their greatest need.
I vow not to leave it.
